Mary Puthisseril Verghese (21 May 1925 - 17 December 1986) was a physician in [[India]] who was among the earliest pioneers of [[Physical medicine and rehabilitation|Physical Medicine and Rehabilitation]] in the country. In 1963, she took charge of what was the first department of Physical Medicine and Rehabilitation with inpatient facility in India at the [[Christian Medical College & Hospital]], [[Vellore]]. She was instrumental in expanding the services of the department with the establishment of the first rehabilitation institute of the country in 1966.<ref>[http://www.cmch-vellore.edu/pdf/introducing%20cmc.pdf For PDF<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.frontlineonnet.com/fl1626/16260890.htm}}</ref>  In recognition of her contributions to the field of medicine, she was awarded the [[Padma Shri]] by the [[Government of India]] in [[Padma Shri Awards (1970â€“1979)|1972]].<ref>[http://india.gov.in/myindia/padmashri_awards_list1.php Padma Shri Awardees - Padma Awards - My India, My Pride - Know India: National Portal of India<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

An award has been instituted in her memory by the Mary Verghese Trust, and the first Dr. Mary Verghese Award for Excellence in Empowering Ability was given in 2012 to [[S. Ramakrishnan (activist)|S. Ramakrishnan]], founder and president of the Amar Seva Sangam.<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/news/states/tamil-nadu/article2908011.ece The Hindu : States / Tamil Nadu : Amar Seva Sangamfounder-president honoured<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Mishra|first=Anil Dutta|title=World Crisis and the Gandhian Way|year=2009|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|location=New Delhi|isbn=8180696006|pages=128|url=http://books.google.co.in/books?id=dh_Bb9zqpBsC&pg=PA128&lpg=PA128&dq=%22amar+seva+sangam%22+ramakrishnan&source=bl&ots=n_KvPRX66C&sig=RNKxt9jzqAnqKlwyben8QGMzvX8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=unR5UJCrBo-3rAeQ4ICYDg&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22amar%20seva%20sangam%22%20ramakrishnan&f=false}}</ref>

== Early life and Education ==
Mary Verghese was born in [[Cherai]] village, [[Cochin]], [[Kerala]], India, in a prosperous family. Her father was a respected leader in the local church and community. She was the seventh of eight children in the family. Elder to her were sisters Annamma, Aleyamma, Thankamma, and brothers John, George and Joseph. Martha was her younger sister. After her schooling at the Union High School in Cherai, Mary attended the [[Maharaja's College]], [[Ernakulam]], for her college studies. She had her graduate training in medicine at the Christian Medical College, Vellore between 1946 and 1952. She got to meet for the first time Dr. [[Ida S. Scudder]], the founder of the institution, at the time of her admission to the course. On completing her training in medicine, aspiring to specialize in [[gynaecology]], she joined the department of gynaecology.<ref>[http://archive.org/stream/takemyhandsthere012760mbp/takemyhandsthere012760mbp_djvu.txt Full text of "Take My Hands The Remarkable Story Of Dr Mary Verghese"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

== Spinal Cord Injury and later years ==
[[File:Mary Verghese Rehabilitation Institute.jpg|thumb|left|Rehabilitation Institute, CMC, Vellore]] It was while working there she was injured in a road crash in 1954 that resulted in complete spinal cord injury. Her injuries were managed by Dr. [[Paul Brand]], who subsequently was her mentor and under whom she learnt surgical skills related to [[leprosy]] rehabilitation. Following a course of rehabilitation at Australian Rehabilitation Center, Perth, Verghese secured a fellowship at the [[Rusk Institute of Rehabilitation Medicine|Institute of Physical Medicine and Rehabilitation, New York]], under [[Howard A. Rusk|Dr. Howard A. Rusk]], a pioneer in the field. On completing her fellowship in 1962, she returned to India to head the [https://sites.google.com/site/pmrcmcvellore/ department of physical medicine and rehabilitation] at Christian Medical College, Vellore.  With the establishment of the rehabilitation institute in 1966, she was heading the first fully functional physical rehabilitation unit in the country. She was involved in providing rehabilitation services primarily for persons with spinal cord injury, leprosy, and brain injury. She continued to work at the Christian Medical College till 1976.<ref>[http://pmrcmcv.tripod.com/silver.htm Silver Jubilee Souvenir of the Rehabilitation Institute, 1991<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[File:Dr.Mary Verghese receiving Padma Shi award.jpg|thumb|Mary Verghese receiving Padma Shri award]] Her biography, titled "Take my hand: the remarkable story of Dr. Mary Verghese", authored by [[Dorothy Clarke Wilson]], was published in 1963.

== Awards ==
In recognition of her contributions to medicine, in particular, to the field of physical rehabilitation in India, Mary Verghese was awarded the Padma Shri by the then President of India, Shri. [[V.V. Giri]] in 1972. She was awarded the World Vision Award in 1985.

== Death and legacy ==
Verghese died in December 1986 at Vellore. The rehabilitation institute established by her has been named in her honor. The Mary Verghese Trust that was started by her in 1986 continues to conduct vocational training programs for persons with physical disabilities. The trust also jointly conducts the annual get-together program for persons with disabilities, the Rehab Mela.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/more-rehabilitation-centres-needed-for-paraplegics/article2912060.ece}}</ref> In 2012, Mary Verghese award foundation was established. The first recipient of the award was Mr. Ramakrishnan from Amar Seva Sangam in [[Aygudi|Ayikudi]]. In 2013, the award was given to [[K. V. Rabiya]].<ref name="Rabia 2013 award">{{cite news|title=Rabia awarded 2013 Dr. Mary Verghese Award|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/mary-verghese-award-presented-to-social-worker-from-kerala/article4423954.ece|accessdate=4 March 2013|newspaper=The Hindu|date=17 February 2013}}</ref> 

